---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const placeholder = "[describe your character here]";

const recipe = `a pixel-art sprite sheet of a single character, retro desktop-pet style: ${placeholder}

layout: one image, an exact grid of 4 columns by 3 rows of 32x32 pixel cells. 128x96 pixels total, or an exact integer multiple of that (256x192, 512x384).

row 1, left to right: idle pose; the same idle pose with one subtle change (a blink, a breath); an alert, startled pose; and a fourth cell left completely empty.
row 2: a walk cycle facing right, 4 frames, left to right.
row 3: a sleeping loop, 4 frames, left to right.

the character is the same size in every cell and stands on the same ground line in every cell. nothing touches or crosses a cell border.
transparent background: a png with alpha. no backdrop, no floor, no border around the image.
crisp 1px pixel art. hard edges, no anti-aliasing, no soft shadows, no glow, no outlines bleeding between cells.`;

const [recipeBefore, recipeAfter] = recipe.split(placeholder);
---

<Layout
  title="onandemo.js — the recipe"
  description="a prompt template you paste into your own image model to get back a sliceable sheet. onandemo never calls a model."
>
  <main class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6">
    <!-- framing -->
    <section class="pt-16 pb-16 sm:pt-24">
      <p class="kicker">the recipe</p>
      <h1
        class="mt-3 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-balance sm:text-6xl"
      >
        bring your own model
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-2xl text-lg text-faded">
        onandemo never calls a model — no key to paste, no queue to wait in. the
        recipe is a battle-tested prompt template: you paste it into whatever
        image model you already have, and the
        <a href="/playground" class="prose-link">playground</a> slices whatever comes
        back into a sheet and a frame map.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="dither"></div>

    <!-- the recipe -->
    <section class="py-16">
      <p class="kicker">copy it</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold">the recipe, verbatim</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 max-w-2xl text-faded">
        fill in the bracket and leave the rest alone. the constraints are the
        point — they're what makes the result sliceable.
      </p>
      <div class="pixel-card mt-8 p-5">
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-3">
          <span class="font-pixel text-xs text-faded"
            >recipe v1 — 4 cols × 3 rows, 32px cells</span
          >
          <button class="pixel-btn" data-copy={recipe}>copy</button>
        </div>
        <pre
          class="mt-4 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed whitespace-pre-wrap text-cream"><code>{recipeBefore}<span class="text-amber">{placeholder}</span>{recipeAfter}</code></pre>
      </div>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl text-sm text-faded">
        what the rows become: row 1 is <code class="font-mono text-cream"
          >idle</code
        > and <code class="font-mono text-cream">alert</code>, row 2 is the run
        facing east — missing directions mirror from there — and row 3 is a
        sleeping antic.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="dither"></div>

    <!-- steps -->
    <section class="py-16">
      <p class="kicker">how to use it</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold">three steps, start to chase</h2>
      <ol class="mt-8 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-3">
        <li class="pixel-card p-5">
          <span class="font-pixel text-xs text-amber">01</span>
          <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-cream">fill in the bracket</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-faded">
            copy the recipe and replace the bracket with your character. one
            line is plenty — “a grumpy slice of toast with little legs” works.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="pixel-card p-5">
          <span class="font-pixel text-xs text-amber">02</span>
          <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-cream">
            paste it into your model
          </h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-faded">
            whatever image model you already have. ask for a png, save what
            comes back. the constraints in the recipe do the negotiating.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li class="pixel-card p-5">
          <span class="font-pixel text-xs text-amber">03</span>
          <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-cream">
            slice it in the playground
          </h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-faded">
            drop the image into the <a href="/playground" class="prose-link"
              >playground</a
            >, set <code class="font-mono text-cream">cellSize</code> to 32, assign
            the states, press chase me.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <div class="dither"></div>

    <!-- caveats -->
    <section class="py-16">
      <p class="kicker">the honest part</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold">what goes wrong</h2>
      <div class="pixel-card mt-8 max-w-3xl p-5">
        <ul class="space-y-4 text-faded">
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="font-pixel text-xs text-amber">+</span>
            <span>
              models rarely land a perfect grid. when the character drifts a few
              pixels between cells, don't re-roll forever — nudge <code
                class="font-mono text-cream">cellSize</code
              > and your cell picks in the playground until the loop steadies.
            </span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="font-pixel text-xs text-amber">+</span>
            <span>
              if your model can't do transparency, ask for a solid magenta
              background instead and key it out in an editor before importing.
              the playground slices; it doesn't remove backgrounds.
            </span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="font-pixel text-xs text-amber">+</span>
            <span>
              when one row comes back broken, regenerate that row as its own
              request. fighting all twelve cells at once is how an evening
              disappears.
            </span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="dither"></div>

    <!-- closer -->
    <section class="py-14">
      <p class="mx-auto max-w-2xl text-center text-faded">
        the slime preset took <span class="text-cream">three states</span> and
        <span class="text-cream">eleven cells</span> — your companion doesn't need
        much.
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
